1.body: Blueprinter is a JSON Object Presenter for Ruby that takes business objects and breaks them down into simple hashes and serializes them to JSON. It can be used in Rails in place of other serializers (like JBuilder or ActiveModelSerializers). It is designed to be simple, direct, and performant.
1.breadcrumbs: Introduction » NOTE This is a WIP for API V2!
1.title: NOTE This is a WIP for API V2!

10.body: Blueprinter has sane defaults for extracting field values from objects, but there are several ways to customize the behavior.
10.breadcrumbs: Blueprinter DSL » Fields » Extracting field values from objects
10.title: Extracting field values from objects

11.body: For Hashes, Blueprinter will look for a key matching the field name - first with a Symbol, then a String. For other objects, Blueprinter will look for a public method matching the field name. The from option can be used to specify a different method or Hash key name.
11.title: Default extraction

12.body:
Return whatever you want from a block. It will be passed a context argument which contains the object being rendered, among other things . Context object fields : blueprint, field, object, options, store, instances field :description do |ctx| ctx.object.description.upcase
end # Blocks can call instance methods defined on your Blueprint
collection :parts, PartBlueprint do |ctx| active_parts ctx.object
end def active_parts(object) object.parts.select(&:active?)
end
12.title: Field blocks

13.body:
Define your own extraction behavior by creating a custom extractor . # For an entire Blueprint or view
options[:extractor] = MyCustomExtractor # For a single field
object :bar, extractor: MyCustomExtractor
13.title: Custom extractors

14.body:
Blueprints can define views to provide different representations of the data. A view inherits everything from its parent but is free to override as needed. In addition to fields, views can define options , partials , formatters , and extensions . At the top level of every Blueprint is an implicit view called default. This view is used when no other is specified. class WidgetBlueprint < ApplicationBlueprint field :name object :category, CategoryBlueprint # The "with_parts" view inherits from "default" and adds a collection of parts view :with_parts do collection :parts, PartBlueprint end # Views can include other views view :full do use :with_parts field :description end
end
14.title: Views

15.body:
Views can exclude fields from a parent: class WidgetBlueprint < ApplicationBlueprint fields :name, :description, :price view :minimal do exclude :description, :price end
end
15.title: Excluding fields

16.body: You can nest views within views, allowing for a hierarchy of inheritance. class WidgetBlueprint < ApplicationBlueprint field :name object :category, CategoryBlueprint view :extended do field :description collection :parts, PartBlueprint # The "extended.with_price" view adds a price field view :with_price do field :price end end
16.title: Nested views

17.body:
When defining an association, you can choose a view from its blueprint: object :widget, WidgetBlueprint[:extended]
collection :widgets, WidgetBlueprint["extended.with_price"]
17.title: Referencing views

18.body:
You can inherit from another blueprint's view: class WidgetBlueprint < ApplicationBlueprint[:with_timestamps] # ...
end
18.breadcrumbs: Blueprinter DSL » Views » Inheriting from views
18.title: Inheriting from views

19.body:
Partials allow you to compose views from reusable components. Just like views, partials can define fields , options , views , other partials , formatters , and extensions . class WidgetBlueprint < ApplicationBlueprint field :name view :foo do use :associations field :foo end view :bar do use :associations, :description field :bar end partial :associations do object :category, CategoryBlueprint collection :parts, PartBlueprint end partial :description do field :description end
end
19.title: Partials

20.body: Blueprinter has two ways of including partials in your views: appending with 'use' and inlining with 'use!' . See examples .
20.breadcrumbs: Blueprinter DSL » Partials » Appending vs. inlining
20.title: Appending vs. inlining

21.body: Partials are appended to your view, giving them the opportunity to override your view's fields, options, etc. Precedence (highest to lowest) is: Definitions in the partial Definitions in the view Definitions inherited from the blueprint/parent views
21.title: Append with 'use'

22.body: Partials are embedded on that line , allowing subsequent lines to override things. Precedence (highest to lowest) is: Definitions in the view after use! Definitions in the partial Definitions in the view before use! Definitions inherited from the blueprint/parent views
22.title: Inline with 'use!'

23.body:
partial :no_empties do options[:field_if] = :og_field_logic options[:object_if] = :og_object_logic options[:collection_if] :og_collection_logic
end # :foo appends the partial, so og_field_logic is used
view :foo do use :no_empties options[:field_if] = :other_field_logic
end # :bar inlines the partial, so other_field_logic takes precedence
view :bar do use! :no_empties options[:field_if] = :other_field_logic
end
23.breadcrumbs: Blueprinter DSL » Partials » Examples of 'use' and 'use!'
23.title: Examples of 'use' and 'use!'

24.body:
Automatically format field values by class. class ApplicationBlueprint # Strip whitespace from all strings format(String) { |val| val.strip } # Format all dates and times using ISO-8601 format Date, :iso8601 format Time, :iso8601 def iso8601(val) val.iso8601 end
end
24.title: Formatters

25.body:
Numerous options can be defined on Blueprints, views, partials, or individual fields. Some can also be passed to render. class WidgetBlueprint < ApplicationBlueprint # Blueprint options apply to all fields, associations, views, and partials in # the Blueprint. They are inherited from the parent class but can be overridden. options[:exclude_if_empty] = true # Field options apply to individual fields or associations. They can override # Blueprint options. field :name, exclude_if_empty: false # Options in views apply to all fields, associations, partials and nested views # in the view. They inherit options from the Blueprint, or from parent views, # and can override them. view :foo do options[:exclude_if_empty] = false end # Options in partials apply to all fields, associations, views, and partials in # the partial. All of these are applied to the views that use the partial. partial :bar do options[:exclude_if_empty] = false end # Some options accept Procs/labmdas. These can call instance methods defined on # your Blueprint. Or you can pass a method name as a symbol. field :foo, if: ->(ctx) { long_complex_check? ctx } field :bar, if: :long_complex_check? def long_complex_check?(ctx) # ... end
end For easier reference, options are grouped into the following categories: Default values : Provide defaults for empty fields Conditional fields : Exclude fields based on conditions Field mapping : Change how field values are extracted from objects Metadata : Wrap or add metadata to the output A note about context objects Options that accept Procs, lambdas, or method names are usually passed a single "context object" argument. It contains the object being rendered, as well as other useful information. See the Context Objects documentation for more information.
25.title: Options

26.title: Default Values

27.title: Conditional Fields

28.body: These options let you change how fields values are extracted from your objects. from Populate the field using a method/Hash key other than the field name. Scope : Field, object, collection field :desc, from: :description extractor Pass a custom extractor class. Scope: Blueprint, view, partial, field, object, collection options[:extractor] = MyCustomExtractor object :category, CategoryBlueprint, extractor: MyCategoryExtractor
28.title: Field mapping

29.body:
These options allow you to add metadata to the rendered output. root Pass a root key to wrap the output. Scope: Blueprint, view, partial, render options[:root] = :data WidgetBlueprint.render(widget, root: :data).to_json meta Add a meta key and data to the wrapped output (requires the root option). Scope: Blueprint, view, partial, render Context object fields : blueprint, value, object, options, store, instances options[:root] = :data
options[:meta] = { page: 1 } # If you pass a Proc/lambda, it can call instance methods defined on the Blueprint
options[:meta] = ->(ctx) { { page: page_num(ctx) } } WidgetBlueprint .render(widget, root: :data, meta: { page: params[:page] }) .to_json
29.title: Metadata

3.body: Generated code documentation can be found at rubydoc.info/gems/blueprinter . Upgrading to API V2? Read the upgrade guide !
3.title: API Docs

30.body: Blueprinter has a powerful extension system with hooks for every step of the serialization lifecycle. Some are included with Blueprinter, others are available as gems, and you can easily write your own using the Extension API .
30.title: Extensions

31.body:
Extensions can be added in your blueprints, views, and partials. They're inherited from parent classes and views, but can be overridden. class MyBlueprint < ApplicationBlueprint extensions << FooExtension.new extensions << BarExtension.new view :minimal do # extensions is a simple Array, so you can add or remove elements extensions.reject! { |ext| ext.is_a? BarExtension } # or simply replace the whole Array self.extensions = [FooExtension.new] end
end
31.title: Using extensions

32.body: These extensions are distributed with Blueprinter. Simply add them to your configuration.
32.title: Included extensions

33.title: Field Order

34.body: blueprinter-activerecord An official extension from the Blueprinter team providing ActiveRecord integration, including automatic preloading of associations based on your Blueprint definitions. Have an extension you'd like to share? Let us know and we may add it to the list!
34.title: External gems

35.body:
# Render the default view to JSON
data = WidgetBlueprint.render(widget).to_json
# or
data = WidgetBlueprint[:default].render(widget).to_json # Render a view to a Hash
data = WidgetBlueprint[:extended].render(widget).to_hash # Render a nested view to JSON
data = WidgetBlueprint["extended.price"].render(widget).to_json TODO render_object, render_collection
35.title: Rendering

36.body: Blueprinter has a rich API for extending the serialization process and reflecting on your blueprints.
36.title: Blueprinter API

37.body: The extensions API offers deep hooks into the serialization process. Read more .
37.title: Extensions

38.body: The reflection API allows your application, or Blueprinter extensions, to introspect on your blueprints options, fields, and views. Read more .
38.title: Reflection

39.body: By creating and using custom extractors, you can change the way field values are extracted from objects. Read more .
39.title: Extractors

4.body:
class WidgetBlueprint < ApplicationBlueprint field :name object :category, CategoryBlueprint collection :parts, PartBlueprint view :extended do field :description object :manufacturer, CompanyBlueprint collection :vendors, CompanyBlueprint end
end # Render the default view to JSON
WidgetBlueprint.render(widget).to_json # Render the extended view to a Hash
WidgetBlueprint[:extended].render(widget).to_hash Look interesting? Learn the DSL!
4.title: Basic Usage

40.body: Context objects are the arguments you'll receive in most of the above APIs. Read more .
40.title: Context Objects

41.body:
Blueprinter has a powerful extension system with hooks for every step of the serialization lifecycle. In fact, many of Blueprinter's features are implemented as built-in extensions! Simply extend the Blueprinter::Extension class, define the hooks you need, and add it to your configuration . class MyExtension < Blueprinter::Extension # Use the exclude_field? hook to exclude certain fields on Tuesdays def exclude_field?(ctx) ctx.field.options[:tuesday] == false && Date.today.tuesday? end
end
41.title: Extensions

42.body: Hooks are called in the following order. Most are passed a context object as an argument. collection? around input_object | input_collection around_blueprint prepare blueprint_fields blueprint_input field_value | object_value | collection_value exclude_field? | exclude_object? | exclude_collection? blueprint_output output_object | output_collection
42.title: Hooks

43.body:
@param Object The object passed to render @return Boolean Whether the object is a collection or a single item @cost Low - run exactly once per render (not called for render_object or render_collection) If any extension with this hook returns true, the object will be considered a collection and rendered as such. For example, the blueprinter-activerecord extension uses this hook to indicate that an ActiveRecord::Relation should be considered a collection. def collection?(object) object.is_a? ArrayLikeThing
end
43.title: collection?

44.body:
@param Context Fields blueprint, object, options, instances, store @cost Low - run exactly once per render Wraps the entire rendering process. Rendering happens during yield, allowing the hook to run code before and after the render. If yield is not called exactly one time, a BlueprinterError is thrown. def around(ctx) # do something before render yield # render # do something after render
end
44.title: around

45.body:
@param Context Fields blueprint, object, options, instances, store @return Object A new or modified version of context.object @cost Low - run exactly once per render Run when render is called with a non-collection object, or when render_object is called. This hook allows you to modify the object before rendering, or even return a new one. Whatever object is returned will be rendered and used as context.object in subsequent hooks. def input_object(ctx) ctx.object
end
45.title: input_object

46.body:
@param Context Fields blueprint, object, options, instances, store @return Object A new or modified version of context.object, which will be array-like @cost Low - run exactly once per render Run when render is called with a collection object, or when render_collection is called. This hook allows you to modify the array-like object before rendering, or even return a new one. Whatever collection is returned will be rendered and used as context.object in subsequent hooks. def input_object(ctx) ctx.object
end
46.title: input_collection

47.body:
@param Context Fields blueprint, object, options, instances, store @cost Medium - run every time any blueprint is rendered Wraps the rendering of a every blueprint. This could be the top-level blueprint or one from an association N levels deep. For collections, it will be called once for each item in the collection. Rendering happens during yield, allowing the hook to run code before and after the render. If yield is not called exactly one time, a BlueprinterError is thrown. def around_blueprint(ctx) # do something before render yield # render # do something after render
end
47.title: around_blueprint

48.body:
@param Context Fields blueprint, object, options, instances, store @cost Low - run once for every blueprint class during render Allows an extension to perform any expensive setup operations for a given blueprint class. context.store is a good place to cache data since it is shared across all hooks and extensions. def prepare(ctx) ctx.store[:my_ext] ||= {} ctx.store[:my_ext][ctx.blueprint.object_id] = setup ctx
end
48.title: prepare

49.body:
@param Context Fields blueprint, object, options, instances, store @return Array<Field | ObjectField | Collection> The fields you want to render in the order you want to render them @cost Low - run once for every blueprint class during render Customize the order fields are rendered in - or strip out certain fields entirely. The included, optional Field Order extension uses this hook. The default behavior is to render all fields in the order they were defined. This example uses the Reflection API to get the fields from the current view, then sort them by name: def blueprint_fields(ctx) ref = ctx.blueprint.class.reflections[:default] ref.ordered.sort_by(&:name)
end
49.title: blueprint_fields

50.body:
@param Context Fields blueprint, object, options, instances, store @return Object A new or modified version of context.object @cost Medium - run every time any blueprint is rendered Run before each blueprint is rendered, allowing you to modify, or return a new, object used for the render. Whatever object is returned will be rendered and used as context.object in subsequent hooks. def blueprint_input(ctx) ctx.object
end
50.title: blueprint_input

51.body:
@param Context Fields blueprint, field, value, object, options, instances, store @return Object The value to be rendered @cost High - run for every field (not object or collection fields) Run after a field value is extracted from context.object. The extracted value is available in context.value. Whatever value you return is used as context.value in subsequent field_value hooks, then run through any formatters and rendered. def field_value(ctx) case ctx when String then ctx.strip else ctx.value end
end
51.title: field_value

52.body:
@param Context Fields blueprint, field, value, object, options, instances, store @return Object The object to be rendered for this field @cost High - run for every object field Run after an object field value is extracted from context.object. The extracted value is available in context.value. Whatever value you return is used as context.value in subsequent object_value hooks, then rendered. def field_value(ctx) case ctx when String then ctx.strip else ctx.value end
end
52.title: object_value

53.body:
@param Context Fields blueprint, field, value, object, options, instances, store @return Object The array-like collection to be rendered for this field @cost High - run for every collection field Run after a collection field value is extracted from context.object. The extracted value is available in context.value. Whatever value you return is used as context.value in subsequent collection_value hooks, then rendered. def collection_value(ctx) ctx.value.compact
end
53.title: collection_value

54.body:
@param Context Fields blueprint, field, value, object, options, instances, store @return Boolean Truthy to exclude the field from the output @cost High - run for every field (not object or collection fields) If any extension with this hook returns truthy, the field will be excluded from the output. The formatted field value is available in context.value. def exclude_field?(ctx) ctx.field.options[:tuesday] == false && Date.today.tuesday?
end
54.title: exclude_field?

55.body:
@param Context Fields blueprint, field, value, object, options, instances, store @return Boolean Truthy to exclude the field from the output @cost High - run for every object field If any extension with this hook returns truthy, the object field will be excluded from the output. The field object value is available in context.value. def exclude_field?(ctx) ctx.field.options[:tuesday] == false && Date.today.tuesday?
end
55.title: exclude_object?

56.body:
@param Context Fields blueprint, field, value, object, options, instances, store @return Boolean Truthy to exclude the field from the output @cost High - run for every collection field If any extension with this hook returns truthy, the collection field will be excluded from the output. The field collection value is available in context.value. def exclude_field?(ctx) ctx.field.options[:tuesday] == false && Date.today.tuesday?
end
56.title: exclude_collection?

57.body:
@param Context Fields blueprint, value, object, options, instances, store @return Hash The Hash to use as this blueprint's serialized output @cost Medium - run every time any blueprint is rendered Run after each blueprint is serialized to a Hash, allowing you to modify the output. The Hash is available in context.value. Whatever Hash is returned will be used as the serialized output for this blueprint. def blueprint_output(ctx) ctx.value.merge({ extra: "data" })
end
57.title: blueprint_output

58.body:
@param Context Fields blueprint, value, object, options, instances, store @return Hash The Hash to use as the final serialized output @cost Low - run once per render (for objects) or render_object Run after the top-level object is fully serialized to a Hash, allowing you to modify the output. The Hash is available in context.value. Whatever Hash is returned will be the final serialized output. def output_object(ctx) ctx.value.merge({ extra: "data" })
end
58.title: output_object

59.title: output_collection

6.body:
Define an ApplicationBlueprint for your blueprints to inherit from. Define common fields , views , partials , formatters , extensions , and options . Library version 2.x class ApplicationBlueprint < Blueprinter::Base field :id
end Library version 1.2.x Version 1.2.x contains both the V1 and V2 APIs, so you must specify V2 in the base class. class ApplicationBlueprint < Blueprinter::V2::Base field :id
end
6.breadcrumbs: Blueprinter DSL » Define your base class
6.title: Define your base class

60.body:
Blueprints may be reflected on to inspect their views, fields, and associations. This is useful for building extensions , and possibly even for some applications. We will use the following blueprint in the examples below: class WidgetBlueprint < ApplicationBlueprint field :name field :description, exclude_if_empty: true object :category, CategoryBlueprint collection :parts, PartBlueprint view :extended do object :manufacturer, CompanyBlueprint[:full] view :with_price do field :price end end
end
60.title: Reflection

62.body:
Here, :default refers to the top level of the blueprint. WidgetBlueprint.reflections.keys
=> [:default, :extended, :"extended.with_price"] You can also reflect directly on a view. Notice that the names are relative : :default now refers to the :extended view, since we called .reflections on :extended. The prefix is also gone from the nested :with_price view. WidgetBlueprint[:extended].reflections.keys
=> [:default, :with_price]
62.title: Views

63.body:
view = WidgetBlueprint.reflections[:default] # Regular fields
view.fields.keys
=> [:name, :description] # Object fields
view.objects.keys
=> [:category] # Collection fields
view.collections.keys
=> [:parts] # All fields in the order they were defined
view.ordered
# returns an array of field objects
63.title: Fields

64.body:
view = WidgetBlueprint.reflections[:default]
field = view.fields[:description] field.name
=> :description field.from
=> :description # the :from option in the DSL field.value_proc
=> nil # the block you passed to the field, if any field.options # all other options passed to the field
=> { exclude_if_empty: true } Object and collection fields have the same metadata as regular fields, plus a blueprint attribute: view = WidgetBlueprint.reflections[:default]
field = view.collection[:parts] # it returns the Blueprint class, so you can continue reflecting
field.blueprint
=> PartBlueprint field.blueprint.reflections[:default].fields
=> # array of fields on the default view of PartBlueprint If you used a view in an object or collection field, you can reflect on that view just like a blueprint: view = WidgetBlueprint.reflections[:extended]
field = view.objects[:manufacturer] field.blueprint.to_s
=> "CompanyBlueprint.full" # Remember, we're reflecting ON the :full view, so the name is relative!
field.blueprint.reflections[:default].fields
=> # array of fields on the :full view of CompanyBlueprint
64.title: Field metadata

65.body: Extractors pull values from the objects you're serializing. The default extractor is smart enough for most use cases, but you can create custom extractors as needed.
65.title: Extractors

66.body:
If context.object is a Hash, it tries symbol then string keys. Otherwise, it calls public_send on the object. class Blueprinter::Extractor # For regular fields def field(ctx) if ctx.object.is_a? Hash ctx.object[ctx.field.from] || ctx.object[ctx.field.from.to_s] else ctx.object.public_send(ctx.field.from) end end # For object fields def object(ctx) field ctx end # For collection fields def collection(ctx) field ctx end
end
66.title: Default Extractor

67.body:
If you're using library version 2.x, subclass from Blueprinter::Extractor. If you're using 1.2.x, subclass from Blueprinter::V2::Extractor. Override the field, object, or collection methods as needed. They'll be passed a context object with the following fields populated: blueprint, field, object, options, instances, store. Note that a new version of your extractor will be initialized for each render, so it's safe to store state inside. class WeirdObjectExtractor < Blueprinter::Extractor def object(ctx) weird_extraction_logic ctx end
end To use your extractor, pass it to the extractor option in your blueprint, view, or field.
67.title: Custom Extractors

68.body: Context objects are the arguments passed to APIs like field blocks , option procs , extension hooks , and extractors . They contain the current blueprint, the object being rendered, and more (depending on the specific API).
68.breadcrumbs: Blueprinter API » Context Objects » Context Objects
68.title: Context Objects

69.body: The current Blueprint instance. You can use this to access the Blueprint's name, options, reflections, and instance methods. Present : Always
69.title: blueprint

7.body:
This blueprint inherits everything from ApplicationBlueprint, then adds a name field and two associations that will render using other blueprints. class WidgetBlueprint < ApplicationBlueprint field :name object :category, CategoryBlueprint collection :parts, PartBlueprint
end There's a lot more you can do with the Blueprinter DSL. Fields are a god place to start!
7.breadcrumbs: Blueprinter DSL » Define blueprints for your models
7.title: Define blueprints for your models

70.body: A struct of the field, object, or collection being rendered. You can use this to access the field's name and options. See rubydoc.info/gems/blueprinter for more information about the Field, ObjectField, and Collection structs. Present : In field blocks, option procs, extractors, and certain extension hooks
70.title: field

71.body: Depending on the API, this will be either the extracted value of the current field, or the entire output of the current Blueprint. Present : Certain option procs and extension hooks
71.title: value

72.body: The object currently being rendered. Present : Always
72.title: object

73.body: The frozen options Hash passed to render. An empty Hash if none was passed. Present : Always
73.title: options

74.body: A Hash for extensions to cache data in. Note that Blueprinter uses this store internally, so be careful not to overwrite Blueprinter's keys (they're all object ids). Present : Always
74.title: store

75.body: A Hash-like interface for creating/fetching class instances. This allows Blueprinter to reuse the same blueprint and extractor instances during a render. You're free to use it, too. See InstanceCache in rubydoc.info/gems/blueprinter for more details. Present : Always
75.title: instances
